System and Network Performance Tuning on Fedora
This chapter covers optimizing the system and network performance on a Fedora Server, including memory management, file system tuning, kernel parameters, and network responsiveness.

1. Upgrade and Update Fedora
............................
Ensure your server has the latest updates and security patches:
sudo dnf update -y

 Always update before tuning your system to avoid compatibility issues.

2.Use Performance Monitoring Tools
....................................
Monitor your system to identify resource bottlenecks:
top – Basic, real-time process monitor:
top

htop – Advanced interactive process monitor (install if missing):
sudo dnf install htop -y
htop

glances – Comprehensive system monitoring:
sudo dnf install glances -y
glances

*Use these tools to check CPU, memory, disk I/O, and network usage.

3. Adjust Swappiness
.......................
Swappiness controls how aggressively Linux uses swap space. Recommended value for servers: 10–20.
Edit sysctl.conf
sudo nano /etc/sysctl.conf

To add or modify:
vm.swappiness = 10

To apply changes:
sudo sysctl -p

4. Optimize File System Mount Options
.....................................
For SSDs and modern storage:
Open /etc/fstab:
sudo nano /etc/fstab

*Add noatime and nodiratime to reduce disk writes. Example:

UUID=<your-uuid> / ext4 defaults,noatime,nodiratime 0 1
Replace <your-uuid> with the actual UUID of your partition (sudo blkid to find it).

5.Enable TRIM for SSDs
.......................
TRIM helps maintain SSD performance over time.
sudo systemctl enable fstrim.timer
sudo systemctl start fstrim.timer


Check status with:
systemctl status fstrim.timer

 6.Optimize Kernel Parameters
..............................
Edit /etc/sysctl.conf to improve network performance:
sudo nano /etc/sysctl.conf

Recommended settings for network tuning
 Increase maximum number of connections
net.core.somaxconn = 1024
net.core.netdev_max_backlog = 5000

Improve TCP connection handling
net.ipv4.tcp_max_syn_backlog = 2048
net.ipv4.tcp_fin_timeout = 30
net.ipv4.tcp_tw_reuse = 1

To apply changes
sudo sysctl -p
Be sure to adjust values according to your server workload.

7.Configure Firewall and Network Settings
.........................................
Use firewalld for optimal firewall rules:
sudo firewall-cmd --list-all
sudo firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-service=http --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload

To review network scripts:
sudo nano /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-<interface>

To fine-tune network performance:
sudo ethtool -G <interface> rx 4096 tx 4096
Replace <interface> with your network interface, e.g., ens160.

 Note:
Always backup configuration files before making changes.
Test any tuning changes in a staging environment if possible.
Monitor system performance continuously using top, htop, or glances.

Combine kernel, network, and storage tuning for optimal overall performance.
